stylometry: This shows how much correlation there is between variables (take an example of demand and price). This value is measured on a scale from -1 to 1. So if the correlation between demand and price was -0.90, that would mean there is a strong negative correlation between the two variables (when price goes up, demand goes down). Alternatively, if the correlation was 0.90 that would mean that there is a strong positive correlation (when price goes up, demand goes up). A poor number for this value would be anything between -0.40 and 0.40 since as this number approaches 0 the correlation between the two variables weakens, and they affect each other less and less.
